MVC Core in Spring Boot (Simple Explanation)

MVC stands for Model-View-Controller, which is a design pattern used in Spring Boot to structure web applications. It helps in separating different parts of your application to make it more organized and manageable.
Three Main Parts of MVC in Spring Boot

    Model (M) â€“ Represents the data and business logic of the application.
        Example: A User class that contains user details like name, email, and age.

    View (V) â€“ Represents the user interface (UI) that the user interacts with.
        Example: An HTML or JSP page that displays user details in a web browser.

    Controller (C) â€“ Handles user requests, processes data, and returns the response.
        Example: A UserController class that processes user-related requests like getting user details or saving user data.

How MVC Works in Spring Boot?

    User sends a request (e.g., clicking a button to get user details).
    Controller receives the request and calls the Model to fetch or process data.
    Model processes the data (e.g., fetching from a database) and sends it back to the Controller.
    Controller sends the data to the View (e.g., an HTML or JSP page).
    View displays the data to the user in a readable format.

Example Code in Spring Boot
Model (User.java)

public class User {
    private String name;
    private int age;

    // Constructor
    public User(String name, int age) {
        this.name = name;
        this.age = age;
    }

    // Getters
    public String getName() { return name; }
    public int getAge() { return age; }
}

Controller (UserController.java)

import org.springframework.stereotype.Controller;
import org.springframework.ui.Model;
import org.springframework.web.bind.annotation.GetMapping;

@Controller
public class UserController {

    @GetMapping("/user")
    public String getUser(Model model) {
        User user = new User("Venkatesh", 25);
        model.addAttribute("user", user);
        return "userView"; // Sends data to the View (userView.html)
    }
}

View (userView.html - Thymeleaf)

<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <title>User Details</title>
</head>
<body>
    <h2>User Details</h2>
    <p>Name: ${user.name}</p>
    <p>Age: ${user.age}</p>
</body>
</html>

Conclusion

    Model handles data (e.g., User class).
    Controller processes requests (@GetMapping("/user")).
    View displays data (userView.html).

This structure makes the application organized, scalable, and easy to manage. Let me know if you need further simplification! ðŸ˜Š
